Artists by calling their video-clips â€œvisualizersâ€ are supposedly arguing that their video is gonna be some visual representation of their final work, or in some cases eventually, the starting point for a new release.

Like a mood board, this could be a way for them to experiment with different concepts without having to develop them into a plot.

author: @sweetiebabysalmon
text:

Visualizer: A less complex music video that is still a music video

LuÃ­s GarÃ§Ã£oClick here to view LuÃ­s GarÃ§Ã£oâ€™s profile
LuÃ­s GarÃ§Ã£o
Digital Content Manager & Pressâ€¦
Published Feb 18, 2021
+ Follow
In todayâ€™s music streaming culture visualizers are now a "thing". But letâ€™s try to demystify and understand the concept first.

The term had since been used over the years in long psychedelic audiovisual experiences and originates from â€œmusic visualizationâ€ functions in electronic media playing software. If youâ€™re above the age of 20 (like me), youâ€™re likely to remember these old visualizers from Windows Media Player; twisting, colorful graphics that moved with the frequencies of the audio.

A visualizer tends to be less developed and fully-fledged than the regular videos and aims to be a simplistic visual intended to accompany the song.

Artists by calling their video-clips â€œvisualizersâ€ are supposedly arguing that their video is gonna be some visual representation of their final work, or in some cases eventually, the starting point for a new release.

Like a mood board, this could be a way for them to experiment with different concepts without having to develop them into a plot."
